WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.880
This is a LibriVox recording.

00:06.340 --> 00:09.300
All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain.

00:10.320 --> 00:17.480
For more information, see LibriVox.blogsum.com.

00:18.400 --> 00:20.560
Today's reading by Hugh Maguire.

00:22.060 --> 00:24.240
Frankenstein by Mary Shelley.

00:24.240 --> 00:26.440
Chapter 24.

00:31.860 --> 00:37.640
My present situation was one in which all voluntary thought was swallowed up and lost.

00:38.680 --> 00:40.540
I was hurried away by fury.

00:41.220 --> 00:44.840
Revenge alone endowed me with strength and composure.

00:45.760 --> 00:50.320
It molded my feelings and allowed me to be calculating and calm.

00:51.080 --> 00:55.700
At periods when otherwise delirium or death would have been my portion.

00:58.360 --> 01:01.140
My first resolution was to quit Geneva forever.

01:01.800 --> 01:09.240
My country, which when I was happy and beloved was dear to me, now in my adversity became hateful.

01:10.400 --> 01:17.140
I provided myself with a sum of money, together with a few jewels which had belonged to my mother, and departed.

01:19.020 --> 01:24.260
And now my wanderings began, which are to cease but with life.

01:26.260 --> 01:34.920
I have traveled a vast portion of the earth and have endured all the hardships which travelers in deserts and barbarous countries are wont to meet.

01:36.240 --> 01:38.100
How I have lived I hardly know.

01:39.040 --> 01:45.140
How many times I stretched my failing limbs upon the sandy plain and prayed for death.

01:46.080 --> 01:48.280
But revenge kept me alive.

01:49.220 --> 01:53.360
I dare not die and leave my adversary in being.

01:55.460 --> 02:03.620
When I quitted Geneva, my first labor was to gain some clue by which I might trace the steps of my fiendish enemy.

02:05.780 --> 02:14.380
But my plan was unsettled, and I wandered many hours round the confines of the town, uncertain what path I should pursue.

02:16.220 --> 02:23.400
As night approached, I found myself at the entrance of the cemetery where William, Elizabeth, and my father reposed.

02:24.680 --> 02:28.540
I entered it and approached the tomb which marked their graves.

02:30.880 --> 02:36.920
Everything was silent, except the leaves of the trees which were gently agitated by the wind.

02:37.720 --> 02:45.160
The night was nearly dark, and the scene would have been solemn and affecting even to an uninterested observer.

02:47.600 --> 02:58.720
The spirits of the departed seemed to flit around and to cast shadow, which was felt but not seen around the head of the mourner.

03:00.340 --> 03:05.940
The deep grief which this scene had at first excited quickly gave way to rage and despair.

03:06.920 --> 03:09.820
They were dead, and I lived.

03:11.200 --> 03:17.580
Their murderer also lived, and to destroy him I must drag out my weary existence.

03:19.100 --> 03:23.420
I knelt on the grass and kissed the earth, and with quivering lips exclaimed,

03:24.340 --> 03:29.960
By the sacred earth on which I kneel, by the shades that wander near me,

03:29.960 --> 03:35.700
By the deep and eternal grief that I feel, I swear, and by thee, O night,

03:36.480 --> 03:42.420
And the spirits that preside over thee, to pursue the demon who caused this misery,

03:42.860 --> 03:49.500
Until he or I shall perish in mortal conflict, for this purpose I will preserve my life.

03:50.000 --> 03:56.880
To execute this dear revenge will I again behold the sun and tread the green herbage of earth,

03:56.880 --> 04:03.420
Which otherwise should vanish from my eyes forever, and I call on you, spirits of the dead,

04:03.940 --> 04:09.080
And on you wandering ministers of vengeance to aid and conduct me in my work.

04:10.180 --> 04:14.560
Let the cursed and hellish monster drink deep of agony.

04:15.620 --> 04:19.160
Let him feel the despair that now torments me.

04:21.020 --> 04:26.900
I had begun my adjuration with solemnity, and an awe which almost assured me

04:26.900 --> 04:32.160
That the shades of my murdered friends heard and approved my devotion.

04:34.260 --> 04:39.240
But the furies possessed me, as I concluded, and rage choked my utterance.

04:41.840 --> 04:46.240
I was answered through the stillness of the night by a loud and fiendish laugh.

04:46.240 --> 04:51.940
It rang on my ears long and heavily. The mountains re-echoed it,

04:52.540 --> 04:56.240
And I felt as if all hell surrounded me with mockery and laughter.

04:57.720 --> 05:00.960
Surely in that moment I should have been possessed by frenzy,

05:01.420 --> 05:05.620
And have destroyed my miserable existence, but that my vow was heard,

05:06.400 --> 05:08.380
And that I was reserved for vengeance.

05:09.420 --> 05:11.440
The laughter died away.

05:12.920 --> 05:16.720
When a well-known and abhorred voice, apparently close to my ear,

05:17.060 --> 05:19.080
Addressed me in an audible whisper.

05:20.200 --> 05:27.160
I am satisfied, miserable wretch. You have determined to live, and I am satisfied.

05:29.480 --> 05:34.680
I darted towards a spot from which the sound proceeded, but the devil eluded my grasp.

05:35.700 --> 05:41.280
Suddenly the broad disk of the moon arose, and shone full upon his ghastly and distorted shape,

05:41.720 --> 05:43.740
As he fled with more than mortal speed.

05:44.700 --> 05:49.000
I pursued him, and for many months this has been my task.

05:49.960 --> 05:54.600
Guided by a slight clue, I followed the windings of the Rhône, but vainly.

05:56.000 --> 06:00.900
The blue Mediterranean appeared, and by a strange chance I saw the fiend enter by night,

06:00.900 --> 06:05.000
And hide himself in a vessel band bound for the Black Sea.

06:05.980 --> 06:11.160
I took my passage in the same ship, but he escaped, I know not how.

06:12.980 --> 06:19.520
Amidst the wilds of Tartary and Russia, although he still evaded me, I have ever followed in his track.

06:20.360 --> 06:26.180
Sometimes the peasants, scared by this horrid apparition, inform me of his path.

06:26.180 --> 06:34.740
Sometimes he himself, who feared that if I lost all trace of him, I should despair and die, left some mark to guide me.

06:36.020 --> 06:41.480
The snows descended on my head, and I saw the print of his huge step on the white plain.

06:43.520 --> 06:48.520
To you first entering on life, to whom care is new and agony unknown,

06:49.240 --> 06:52.240
How can you understand what I have felt and still feel?

06:52.240 --> 06:58.800
Cold, want, and fatigue, were the least pains of which I was destined to endure.

07:00.000 --> 07:04.980
I was cursed by some devil, and carried about with me my eternal hell.

07:06.200 --> 07:11.640
Yet still a spirit of good followed and directed my step, and when I most murmured,

07:12.620 --> 07:16.420
Would suddenly extricate me from seemingly insurmountable difficulties.

07:18.280 --> 07:22.740
Sometimes, when nature, overcome by hunger, sunk under the exhaustion,

07:23.540 --> 07:28.600
A repast was prepared for me in the desert, that restored and inspirited me.

07:30.320 --> 07:34.400
The fair was indeed coarse, such as the peasants of the country ate,

07:35.120 --> 07:40.680
But I will not doubt that it was set there by the spirits that I had invoked to aid me.

07:40.680 --> 07:46.300
Often, when all was dry, the heavens cloudless, and I was parched by thirst,

07:47.240 --> 07:52.980
A slight cloud would bedim the sky, and shed a few drops that revived me and vanished.

07:55.880 --> 08:01.920
I followed, when I could, the courses of the rivers, but the demon generally avoided these,

08:02.420 --> 08:05.740
As it was here that the population of the country chiefly collected.

08:06.440 --> 08:13.940
In other places human beings were seldom seen, and I generally subsisted on the wild animals that crossed my path.

08:14.640 --> 08:19.740
I had money with me, and gained the friendship of the villagers by distributing it,

08:20.200 --> 08:25.160
While I brought with me some food that I had killed, which after taking small part,

08:25.720 --> 08:30.100
I always presented to those who had provided me with fire and utensils for cooking.

08:31.280 --> 08:35.000
My life, as it passed thus, was indeed hateful to me,

08:35.120 --> 08:39.740
And it was during sleep alone that I could taste joy. Oh, blessed sleep!

08:40.860 --> 08:46.020
Often, when most miserable, I sank to repose, and my dreams lulled me even to rapture.

08:47.040 --> 08:51.880
The spirits that guarded me had provided these moments, or rather hours, of happiness,

08:51.960 --> 08:55.800
That I might retain strength to fulfill my pilgrimage.

08:57.660 --> 09:02.460
Deprived of this respite, I should have sunk under my hardships.

09:04.480 --> 09:08.120
During the day I was sustained and inspirited by the hope of night,

09:08.460 --> 09:13.010
For in sleep I saw my friends, my wife, and my beloved country.

09:15.160 --> 09:22.000
Again I saw the benevolent countenance of my father, heard the silver tones of my Elizabeth's voice,

09:22.000 --> 09:26.160
And beheld Clerval, enjoying health and youth.

09:27.980 --> 09:34.200
Often, when wearied by a toilsome march, I persuaded myself that I was dreaming until night should come,

09:34.620 --> 09:39.640
And that I should then enjoy reality in the arms of my dearest friends.

09:41.720 --> 09:48.000
What agonizing fondness did I feel for them? How did I cling to their fears, to their...

09:51.640 --> 09:57.920
What agonizing fondness did I feel for them? How did I cling to their dream forms,

09:58.040 --> 10:03.220
As sometimes they haunted even my waking hours, and persuade myself that they still lived?

10:05.520 --> 10:10.160
At such moments, vengeance, that burned within me, died in my heart,

10:10.540 --> 10:13.700
And I pursued my path towards the destruction of the demon,

10:14.580 --> 10:16.740
More as a task enjoined by heaven,

10:16.740 --> 10:21.040
As the mechanical impulse of some power of which I was unconscious,

10:22.200 --> 10:24.420
Than as the ardent desire of my soul.

10:28.520 --> 10:31.840
What his feelings were whom I pursued I cannot know.

10:33.020 --> 10:36.900
Sometimes, indeed, he left marks in writing on the bark of the trees,

10:37.040 --> 10:41.140
Or cut in stone that guided me and instigated my fury.

10:42.380 --> 10:44.300
My reign is not yet over.

10:46.080 --> 10:49.320
These words were legible in one of these inscriptions.

10:49.920 --> 10:53.440
You live, and my power is complete. Follow me.

10:54.280 --> 10:57.240
I seek the everlasting ices of the north,

10:57.700 --> 11:02.140
Where you will feel the misery of cold and frost to which I am impassive.

11:03.180 --> 11:07.940
You will find near this place, if you follow not too tardily, a dead hare.

11:08.520 --> 11:11.960
Eat and be refreshed. Come on, my enemy.

11:12.900 --> 11:15.620
We have yet to wrestle for our lives,

11:16.660 --> 11:19.920
But many hard and miserable hours must you endure,

11:20.700 --> 11:22.720
Until that period shall arrive.

11:25.700 --> 11:29.280
Scoffing devil, again do I vow vengeance,

11:30.140 --> 11:34.580
Again do I devote thee, miserable fiend to torture and death.

11:35.840 --> 11:39.360
Never will I give up my search until he or I perish,

11:39.360 --> 11:43.060
And then with what ecstasy shall I join my Elizabeth

11:43.060 --> 11:46.440
And my departed friends who even now prepare for me

11:46.440 --> 11:50.400
The reward of my tedious toil and horrible pilgrimage.

11:52.140 --> 11:56.780
As I still pursued my journey to the northward, the snows thickened,

11:56.780 --> 12:00.840
And the cold increased in a degree almost too severe to support.

12:02.800 --> 12:05.500
The peasants were shut up in their hovels,

12:05.500 --> 12:09.540
And only a few of the most hardy ventured forth to seize the animals

12:09.540 --> 12:13.640
Whom starvation had forced from their hiding places to seek for prey.

12:15.600 --> 12:19.700
The rivers were covered with ice, and no fish could be procured,

12:20.620 --> 12:23.880
And thus I was cut off from my chief article of maintenance.

12:25.840 --> 12:29.960
The triumph of my enemy increased with the difficulty of my labors.

12:31.340 --> 12:33.920
One inscription that he left was in these words,

12:34.840 --> 12:37.640
Prepare, your toil is only begin.

12:38.640 --> 12:43.480
Wrap yourself in furs, and provide food, for we shall soon enter

12:43.480 --> 12:49.080
Upon a journey where your sufferings will satisfy my everlasting hatred.

12:52.240 --> 12:56.540
My courage and perseverance were invigorated by these scoffing words.

12:57.380 --> 13:02.320
I resolved not to fail in my purpose, and calling on heaven to support me,

13:02.320 --> 13:06.320
I continued with unabated fervour to traverse immense deserts,

13:07.020 --> 13:12.040
Until the ocean appeared at a distance, and formed the utmost boundary of the horizon.

13:13.880 --> 13:17.880
Oh, how unlike it was to the blue seasons of the south!

13:18.760 --> 13:25.260
Covered with ice, it was only to be distinguished from land by its superior wildness and ruggedness.

13:26.320 --> 13:31.720
The Greeks wept for joy when they beheld the Mediterranean from the hills of Asia,

13:31.720 --> 13:35.440
And hailed with rapture the boundary of their toils.

13:38.280 --> 13:45.010
I did not weep, but I knelt down, and with a full heart thanked my guiding spirits for conducting me

13:45.340 --> 13:51.740
In safety to the place where I hoped, not withstanding my adversary's jibe,

13:52.040 --> 13:54.540
To meet and grapple with him.

13:57.260 --> 14:02.600
Some weeks before this period I had procured a sled and dogs,

14:02.900 --> 14:06.040
And thus traversed the snows with inconceivable speed.

14:07.080 --> 14:11.900
I know not whether the fiend possessed the same advantages, but I found that as before

14:11.900 --> 14:16.620
I had daily lost ground in the pursuit I now gained on him,

14:16.840 --> 14:21.760
So much so that when I first saw the ocean he was but one day's journey in advance,

14:21.760 --> 14:25.540
And I hoped to intercept him before he should reach the beach.

14:28.000 --> 14:34.240
With new courage therefore I pressed on, and in two days arrived at a wretched hamlet on the seashore.

14:35.280 --> 14:40.820
I inquired of the inhabitants concerning the fiend and gained accurate information.

14:42.480 --> 14:49.200
A gigantic monster, they said, had arrived the night before, armed with a gun and many pistols,

14:49.200 --> 14:55.320
Putting to flight the inhabitants of a solitary cottage through fear of his terrific appearance.

14:55.900 --> 15:02.860
He had carried off their store of winter food and, placing it in a sledge, to draw,

15:03.720 --> 15:07.640
Which he had seized on a numerous drove of trained dogs.

15:08.360 --> 15:14.300
He had harnessed them, and the same night, to the joy of the horror-struck villagers,

15:14.300 --> 15:19.080
Had pursued his journey across the sea in a direction that led to no land,

15:20.000 --> 15:27.300
And they conjectured that he must speedily be destroyed by the breaking of the ice frozen by the eternal frosts.

15:29.640 --> 15:33.500
On hearing this information I suffered a temporary access of despair.

15:34.660 --> 15:39.800
He had escaped me, and I must commence a destructive and almost endless journey

15:39.800 --> 15:46.180
Across the mountainous ices of the ocean, amidst cold that few of the inhabitants could long endure,

15:46.500 --> 15:52.120
And which I, the native of a genial and sunny climate, could not hope to survive.

15:53.840 --> 15:59.880
Yet at the idea that the fiend should live and be triumphant, my rage and vengeance returned,

16:00.500 --> 16:04.060
And, like a mighty tide, overwhelmed every other feeling.

16:04.880 --> 16:09.620
After a slight repose, during which the spirits of the dead hovered round,

16:10.100 --> 16:14.400
And instigated me to toil in revenge, I prepared for my journey.

16:16.480 --> 16:22.080
I exchanged my land-sledge for one fashioned for the inequalities of the frozen ocean,

16:22.680 --> 16:25.300
And purchasing a plentiful stock of presisions.

16:28.120 --> 16:30.060
I departed from land.

16:32.200 --> 16:35.580
I cannot guess how many days have passed since then,

16:35.760 --> 16:41.560
But I have endured misery which nothing but the eternal sentiment of a just retribution,

16:41.940 --> 16:45.120
Burning within my heart, could have enabled me to support.

16:46.360 --> 16:51.540
Immense and rugged mountains of ice often barred up my passage,

16:51.800 --> 16:56.360
And I often heard the thunder of the ground sea, which threatened my destruction.

16:57.120 --> 17:02.420
But again the frost came and made the paths of the sea secure.

17:04.620 --> 17:10.960
By the quantity of provision which I had consumed, I should guess that I had passed three weeks in this journey,

17:11.480 --> 17:17.200
And the continual protraction of hope returning back upon the heart,

17:17.900 --> 17:22.500
Often wrung bitter drops of despondency and grief from my eyes.

17:23.720 --> 17:27.680
Despair had indeed almost secured her prey,

17:28.180 --> 17:30.980
And I should soon have sunk beneath this misery.

17:33.360 --> 17:40.800
Once after the poor animals that conveyed me had with incredible toil gained the summit of a sloping ice mountain,

17:41.400 --> 17:47.500
And one, sinking under his fatigue, died, I viewed the expanse before me with anguish,

17:47.900 --> 17:51.660
When suddenly my eye caught a dark speck upon the dusky plain.

17:52.500 --> 17:56.100
I strained my sight to discover what it could be,

17:56.580 --> 18:00.480
And uttered a wild cry of ecstasy when I distinguished a sledge,

18:00.880 --> 18:04.220
And the distorted proportions of a well-known form within.

18:05.800 --> 18:10.100
Oh, with what burning gush did hope revisit my heart,

18:10.600 --> 18:14.760
Warm tears filled my eyes, which I hastily wiped away,

18:15.400 --> 18:19.160
That they might not intercept the view I had of the demon.

18:19.880 --> 18:23.880
But still my sight was dimmed by the burning drops,

18:24.260 --> 18:29.120
Until, giving way to the emotions that oppressed me, I wept aloud.

18:32.340 --> 18:35.400
But this was not the time for delay.

18:36.700 --> 18:39.760
I disencumbered the dogs of their dead companion,

18:40.280 --> 18:42.600
Gave them a plentiful portion of food,

18:42.800 --> 18:46.120
And after an hour's rest, which was absolutely necessary,

18:46.120 --> 18:49.980
And yet, which was bitterly irksome to me, I continued my route.

18:51.680 --> 18:56.060
The sledge was still visible, nor did I again lose sight of it,

18:56.220 --> 18:58.940
Except at the moment when, for a short time,

18:59.000 --> 19:02.540
Some ice rock concealed it with its intervening crags.

19:03.740 --> 19:06.180
I indeed perceptibly gained on it,

19:06.180 --> 19:08.760
And when, after nearly two days' journey,

19:09.140 --> 19:12.920
I beheld my enemy at no more than a mile distant,

19:12.920 --> 19:15.540
My heart bounded within me.

19:16.940 --> 19:21.020
But now, when I appeared almost within grasp of my foe,

19:21.140 --> 19:22.960
My hopes were suddenly extinguished,

19:22.980 --> 19:26.700
And I lost all trace of him more utterly than I had ever done before.

19:27.920 --> 19:30.880
A ground sea was heard, the thunder of its progress

19:30.880 --> 19:33.580
As the waters rolled and swelled beneath me,

19:33.820 --> 19:36.320
Became every moment more ominous and terrific.

19:37.080 --> 19:38.700
I pressed on, but in vain.

19:39.180 --> 19:41.660
The wind rose and the sea roared,

19:41.660 --> 19:44.780
And, as with the mighty shock of an earthquake,

19:45.000 --> 19:49.020
It split and cracked with a tremendous and overwhelming sound.

19:49.920 --> 19:51.500
The work was soon finished.

19:51.960 --> 19:56.140
In a few minutes a tumultuous sea rolled between me and my enemy,

19:56.420 --> 19:59.060
And I was left drifting on a scattered piece of ice

19:59.060 --> 20:00.920
That was continually lessening,

20:01.120 --> 20:03.720
And thus preparing for me a hideous death.

20:06.120 --> 20:09.500
In this manner many an appalling hours passed.

20:09.500 --> 20:11.480
Several of my dogs died,

20:11.860 --> 20:15.500
And I myself was about to sink under the accumulation of distress

20:15.500 --> 20:18.140
When I saw your vessel riding at anchor,

20:18.800 --> 20:21.840
And holding forth to me hopes of succor and life.

20:23.640 --> 20:26.900
I had no conception that vessels ever came so far north

20:26.900 --> 20:28.480
And was astounded at the sight.

20:29.380 --> 20:32.600
I quickly destroyed part of my sledge to construct oars,

20:32.820 --> 20:35.940
And by these means was enabled, with infinite fatigue,

20:36.120 --> 20:38.640
To move my ice raft in the direction of your ship.

20:39.880 --> 20:42.800
I had determined, if you were going southward,

20:43.000 --> 20:45.880
Still to trust myself to the mercy of the seas

20:45.880 --> 20:47.660
Rather than abandon my purpose.

20:48.740 --> 20:51.980
I hoped to induce you to grant me a boat

20:52.720 --> 20:54.860
With which I could pursue my enemy,

20:55.700 --> 20:57.520
But your direction was northward.

20:58.080 --> 21:00.740
You took me on board when my vigor was exhausted,

21:01.520 --> 21:04.940
And I should soon have sunk under my multiple-eyed hardships

21:04.940 --> 21:06.760
Into a death which I still dread,

21:06.760 --> 21:08.880
For my task is unfulfilled.

21:11.800 --> 21:15.200
Oh, when will my guiding spirit in conducting me to the demon

21:15.200 --> 21:17.420
Allow me the rest I so much desire,

21:18.160 --> 21:21.700
Or must I die, and he yet live?

21:23.020 --> 21:27.420
If I do, swear to me, Walton, that he shall not escape,

21:28.400 --> 21:32.140
That you will seek him and satisfy my vengeance in his death.

21:33.020 --> 21:36.080
And do I dare to ask of you to undertake my pilgrimage

21:36.080 --> 21:38.260
To endure the hardships that I have undergone?

21:39.100 --> 21:42.040
No, I am not so selfish.

21:42.980 --> 21:45.000
Yet when I am dead, if he should appear,

21:45.540 --> 21:48.420
If the ministers of vengeance should conduct him to you,

21:48.580 --> 21:50.340
Swear that he shall not live,

21:51.120 --> 21:55.080
Swear that he shall not triumph over my accumulated woes,

21:55.780 --> 21:58.440
And survive to add to the list of his dark crimes.

21:59.440 --> 22:01.700
He is eloquent and persuasive,

22:02.180 --> 22:05.640
And once his words had even power over my heart,

22:05.640 --> 22:10.660
But trust him not, his soul is as hellish as his form,

22:10.980 --> 22:15.040
Full of treachery and fiendlike malice.

22:15.980 --> 22:16.740
Hear him not.

22:18.580 --> 22:20.860
Call on him the mains of William, Justine,

22:21.860 --> 22:24.820
Clairvaux, Elizabeth, my father and the wretched Victor,

22:25.560 --> 22:27.440
And thrust your sword into his heart.

22:28.440 --> 22:32.060
I will hover near and direct the steel aright.

22:35.620 --> 22:37.560
Walton, in continuation.

22:38.540 --> 22:41.720
August 26th, 17 something.

22:46.080 --> 22:49.300
You have read this strange and terrific story, Margaret.

22:51.280 --> 22:54.120
And do you not feel your blood congeal with horror,

22:54.460 --> 22:56.560
Like that which even now curdles mine?

22:58.380 --> 23:00.700
Sometimes, seized with sudden agony,

23:00.700 --> 23:02.800
He could not continue his tale.

23:03.340 --> 23:05.880
At others his voice broken, yet piercing,

23:06.540 --> 23:09.520
Uttered with difficulty the words so replete with anguish.

23:10.560 --> 23:14.900
His fine and lovely eyes were now lighted up with indignation,

23:15.440 --> 23:17.700
Now subdued to downcast sorrow,

23:18.380 --> 23:20.940
And quenched in infinite wretchedness.

23:22.460 --> 23:25.820
Sometimes he commanded his countenance and tones,

23:26.620 --> 23:30.000
And related the most horrible incidents with a tranquil voice,

23:30.000 --> 23:32.420
Suppressing every mark of agitation.

23:33.520 --> 23:35.620
Then, like a volcano bursting forth,

23:35.820 --> 23:39.580
His face would suddenly change to an expression of the wildest rage,

23:40.140 --> 23:41.090
As he shrieked out,

23:42.320 --> 23:44.340
Impreciations on his persecutor.

23:46.720 --> 23:48.020
His tale is connected,

23:48.400 --> 23:50.900
And told with an appearance of the simplest truth.

23:51.820 --> 23:55.340
Yet I own to you that the letters of Felix and Saffy,

23:55.520 --> 23:56.660
Which he showed me,

23:56.760 --> 23:59.520
And the apparition of the monster seen from our ship,

23:59.520 --> 24:02.780
Brought to me a greater conviction of the truth of his narrative

24:02.780 --> 24:04.520
Than his assertiveness,

24:05.980 --> 24:07.800
However earnest and connected.

24:10.500 --> 24:12.740
Such a monster has, then, real existence.

24:13.540 --> 24:14.520
I cannot doubt it.

24:15.360 --> 24:17.700
Yet I am lost in surprise and admiration.

24:19.260 --> 24:22.400
Sometimes I endeavored to gain from Frankenstein

24:22.400 --> 24:24.740
The particulars of his creature's formation,

24:25.000 --> 24:26.520
But on this point he was impenetrable.

24:28.040 --> 24:30.800
Are you mad, my friend, said he,

24:31.180 --> 24:34.060
Or whither does your senseless curiosity lead you?

24:34.340 --> 24:38.140
Would you also create for yourself and the world a demonical enemy?

24:38.520 --> 24:39.540
Peace, peace!

24:40.220 --> 24:43.180
Learn my miseries and do not seek to increase your own.

24:45.080 --> 24:48.120
Frankenstein discovered that I made notes concerning his history.

24:48.880 --> 24:50.220
He asked to see them,

24:50.540 --> 24:53.820
And then himself corrected and augmented them in many places,

24:54.440 --> 24:56.400
But principally in giving me the life

24:56.400 --> 25:00.020
And spirit to the conversations he held with his enemy.

25:01.500 --> 25:04.220
Since you have preserved my narration, said he,

25:04.760 --> 25:09.620
I would not that a mutilated one should go down to posterity.

25:11.340 --> 25:12.860
Thus has a week passed away

25:12.860 --> 25:14.960
While I have listened to the strangest tale

25:14.960 --> 25:16.660
That ever imagination formed.

25:18.500 --> 25:20.640
My thoughts and every feeling of my soul

25:20.640 --> 25:23.340
Have been drunk up by the interest of my guest,

25:23.340 --> 25:28.300
Which this tale and his own elevated and gentle manners have created.

25:29.680 --> 25:32.660
I wish to soothe him, yet I can counsel one

25:32.660 --> 25:34.660
So indefinitely miserable,

25:36.400 --> 25:39.740
So destitute of every hope and consolation.

25:42.120 --> 25:45.340
Frankenstein discovered that I made notes concerning his history.

25:45.960 --> 25:47.300
He asked to see them,

25:47.520 --> 25:50.900
And then himself corrected and augmented them in many places,

25:50.900 --> 25:53.220
But principally in giving me the life

25:53.220 --> 25:55.860
And spirit to the conversations he held with his enemy.

25:57.720 --> 26:00.800
Since you have preserved my narration, said he,

26:01.200 --> 26:05.380
I would not that a mutilated one should go down to posterity.

26:07.100 --> 26:08.620
Thus has a week passed away

26:08.620 --> 26:10.740
While I have listened to the strangest tale

26:10.740 --> 26:12.520
That ever imagination formed.

26:13.340 --> 26:15.540
My thoughts and every feeling of my soul

26:15.540 --> 26:18.180
Have been drunk up by the interest of my guest,

26:18.180 --> 26:22.200
Which this tale and his own elevated gentle manners have created.

26:23.860 --> 26:27.140
I wish to soothe him, yet I can counsel one

26:27.140 --> 26:28.640
So infinitely miserable,

26:28.960 --> 26:31.840
So destitute of every hope and consolation to live.

26:33.200 --> 26:36.140
Oh no, the only joy that he can now know

26:36.140 --> 26:38.800
Will be when he composes his shattered spirit

26:38.800 --> 26:40.240
To peace and death.

26:41.740 --> 26:43.240
Yet he enjoys one comfort,

26:43.680 --> 26:46.360
The offspring of solitude and delirium.

26:46.360 --> 26:51.180
He believes that when in dreams he holds converse with his friends

26:51.180 --> 26:55.340
And derives from that communion consolation for his miseries

26:55.340 --> 26:57.120
Or excitements to his vengeance,

26:57.740 --> 27:00.060
That they are not the creations of his fancy,

27:00.440 --> 27:05.060
But the beings themselves who visit from the regions of a remote world.

27:05.960 --> 27:09.900
This faith gives a solemnity to his reveries

27:09.900 --> 27:13.780
That render them to me almost as imposing and interesting as truth.

27:16.380 --> 27:18.940
Our conversations are not always confined

27:19.300 --> 27:21.780
To his own history and misfortunes.

27:23.460 --> 27:27.420
On every point of general literature he displays unbounded knowledge

27:27.420 --> 27:29.860
And a quick and piercing apprehension.

27:30.880 --> 27:32.940
His eloquence is forcible and touching,

27:33.660 --> 27:36.960
Nor can I hear him when he relates a pathetic incident

27:36.960 --> 27:41.940
Or endeavors to move the passions of pity or love without tears.

27:42.520 --> 27:46.160
What a glorious creature must he have been in the days of his prosperity

27:46.460 --> 27:49.760
When he is thus noble and godlike in ruin.

27:50.300 --> 27:54.360
He seems to feel his own worth in the greatness of his fall.

27:56.960 --> 28:01.760
When younger, said he, I believe myself destined for some great enterprise.

28:02.360 --> 28:03.660
My feelings are profound,

28:03.920 --> 28:08.340
But I possessed a coolness of judgment that fitted me for illustrious achievements.

28:08.940 --> 28:12.980
This sentiment of worth, of my nature, supported me

28:12.980 --> 28:15.020
When others would have been oppressed.

28:16.020 --> 28:19.080
For I deemed it criminal to throw away in useless grief

28:19.080 --> 28:22.300
Those talents that might be useful to my fellow creatures.

28:24.000 --> 28:26.120
When I reflected on the work I had completed

28:26.120 --> 28:31.660
No less than one, no lesser one than the creation of a sensitive and rational animal.

28:32.260 --> 28:35.500
I could not rank myself with the herd of common projectors.

28:35.500 --> 28:41.120
But this thought, which supported me in my commencement of my career,

28:41.560 --> 28:44.260
Now serves only to plunge me lower in the dust.

28:45.460 --> 28:48.640
All my speculations and hopes are as nothing and,

28:49.220 --> 28:53.240
Like the archangel who aspired to omnipotence,

28:53.820 --> 28:55.560
I am chained to an eternal hell.

28:56.700 --> 28:58.520
My imagination was vivid,

28:59.360 --> 29:02.340
Yet my powers of analysis and application were intense.

29:03.160 --> 29:06.660
By the union of these qualities I conceived the idea

29:06.660 --> 29:09.180
And executed the creation of a man.

29:11.480 --> 29:14.060
Even now I cannot recollect, without passion,

29:14.520 --> 29:16.760
My reveries while the work was incomplete.

29:17.720 --> 29:19.740
I trod heaven in my thoughts,

29:20.120 --> 29:23.940
Now exulting in my powers, now burning with the idea of their effects.

29:24.920 --> 29:29.180
From my infancy I was imbued with high hopes and lofty ambition.

29:30.220 --> 29:31.940
But how I am sunk.

29:33.640 --> 29:36.400
Oh, my friend, if you had known me as I once was,

29:36.640 --> 29:39.300
You would not recognize me in this state of degradation.

29:40.600 --> 29:42.700
Despondency rarely visited my heart.

29:43.520 --> 29:46.660
A high destiny seemed to bear me on until I fell,

29:47.120 --> 29:48.840
Never, never again to rise.

29:52.680 --> 29:55.700
Must I then lose this admirable being?

29:55.700 --> 29:58.040
I have longed for a friend.

29:58.540 --> 30:01.760
I have sought one who would sympathize with and love me.

30:02.120 --> 30:05.100
Behold, on these desert seas I have found such a one.

30:05.620 --> 30:08.880
But I have fear I have gamed him

30:08.880 --> 30:11.400
Only to know his value and lose him.

30:12.240 --> 30:14.580
I would reconcile him to life.

30:15.520 --> 30:17.180
But he repulses the idea.

30:18.320 --> 30:20.140
I thank you, Walton, he said,

30:20.580 --> 30:23.720
For your kind intentions towards so miserable a wretch.

30:23.720 --> 30:27.700
But when you speak of new tides and fresh affections,

30:29.480 --> 30:32.280
Think you that any can replace those who are gone.

30:32.640 --> 30:36.000
Can any man be to me as Clairvaux was,

30:36.620 --> 30:38.340
Or any woman another Elizabeth?

30:39.960 --> 30:42.340
Even where the affections are not strongly moved

30:42.340 --> 30:43.940
By any superior excellence,

30:44.660 --> 30:47.800
The companions of our childhood always possess

30:47.800 --> 30:49.720
A certain power over our minds,

30:49.720 --> 30:52.920
Which hardly any later friend can obtain.

30:54.440 --> 30:58.180
They know our infinite dispositions,

30:58.180 --> 31:01.520
Which, however they may be afterwards modified,

31:01.760 --> 31:03.000
Are never eradicated.

31:03.680 --> 31:05.300
They can judge of our actions

31:05.300 --> 31:07.060
With more certain conclusions

31:07.720 --> 31:09.780
As to the integrity of our motives.

31:11.600 --> 31:13.560
A sister or a brother can never,

31:13.680 --> 31:16.500
Unless indeed such symptoms have been shown early,

31:16.500 --> 31:19.700
Suspect the other of fraud or false dealings,

31:19.900 --> 31:23.160
When another friend, however strongly he may be attached,

31:23.860 --> 31:25.240
May, in spite of himself,

31:25.820 --> 31:27.480
Be contemplated with suspicion.

31:29.880 --> 31:32.340
But I enjoyed friends dear not only

31:32.340 --> 31:34.100
Through habit and association,

31:34.500 --> 31:35.800
But from their own merits.

31:36.760 --> 31:39.820
And wherever I am, the soothing voice of my Elizabeth

31:39.820 --> 31:42.940
And the conversations of Clairvaux

31:42.940 --> 31:45.600
Will ever be whispered in my ear.

31:46.600 --> 31:47.540
They are dead,

31:48.140 --> 31:50.940
But one feeling in such a solitude

31:50.940 --> 31:53.400
Can persuade me to preserve my life.

31:54.860 --> 31:57.580
If I were engaged in any high undertaking

31:58.440 --> 31:59.800
Or design,

32:00.900 --> 32:03.000
Fraught with extensive utility

32:03.000 --> 32:04.400
To my fellow creatures,

32:04.920 --> 32:06.640
Then I could live to fulfill it,

32:06.640 --> 32:08.260
But such is not my destiny.

32:08.720 --> 32:11.040
I must pursue and destroy the being

32:11.040 --> 32:12.860
To whom I have gave existence.

32:13.720 --> 32:17.180
Then my lot on earth will be fulfilled,

32:18.120 --> 32:19.180
And I may die.

32:23.220 --> 32:24.420
September 2nd.

32:24.420 --> 32:25.460
My beloved sister,

32:26.360 --> 32:28.540
I write to you encompassed by peril

32:28.540 --> 32:31.620
And ignorant whether I am ever doomed to see again

32:31.620 --> 32:34.460
My dear England and the dearer friends that inhabit it.

32:34.780 --> 32:37.680
I am surrounded by mountains of ice which admit of no escape

32:37.680 --> 32:40.240
And threaten every moment to crush my vessel.

32:41.220 --> 32:43.740
The brave fellows who I have persuaded to be

32:43.740 --> 32:46.660
My companions look towards me for aid,

32:47.040 --> 32:48.540
But I have none to bestow.

32:49.400 --> 32:51.780
There is something terribly appalling in our situation,

32:51.860 --> 32:54.260
Yet my courage and hopes do not desert me.

32:54.700 --> 32:57.560
Yet it is terrible to reflect that the lives of all these men

32:57.560 --> 32:59.160
Are endangered through me.

32:59.680 --> 33:02.980
If we are lost, my mad, mad schemes are the cause.

33:06.260 --> 33:07.260
And what, Margaret,

33:07.280 --> 33:08.740
Will be the state of your mind?

33:09.100 --> 33:10.860
You will not hear of my destruction,

33:11.140 --> 33:13.220
And you will anxiously await my return.

33:13.760 --> 33:16.340
Years will pass and you will have visiting of despair

33:16.340 --> 33:17.880
And yet be tortured by hope.

33:18.680 --> 33:21.880
Oh, my beloved sister, the sickening failing

33:21.880 --> 33:24.600
Of your heartfelt expectations is in prospect

33:24.600 --> 33:26.700
More terrible to me than my own death,

33:27.340 --> 33:29.360
But you have a husband and lovely children.

33:29.680 --> 33:33.480
You may be happy. Heaven bless you and make you so.

33:34.820 --> 33:36.740
My unfortunate guest regards me

33:36.740 --> 33:38.100
With a tenderest compassion.

33:38.940 --> 33:41.960
He endeavours to fill me with hope and talks as if life

33:41.960 --> 33:43.520
Were a possession which he valued.

33:44.200 --> 33:47.040
He reminds me how often the same accidents have happened

33:47.040 --> 33:50.000
To other navigators who have attempted this sea.

33:50.680 --> 33:53.260
And in spite of myself, he fills me with cheerful

33:54.320 --> 33:54.880
Auguries.

33:55.900 --> 33:58.280
Even the sailors feel the power of his eloquence.

33:58.520 --> 34:00.320
When he speaks, they no longer despair.

34:00.980 --> 34:04.480
He rouses their energies, and while they hear his voice,

34:04.600 --> 34:08.180
They believe these vast mountains of ice

34:08.180 --> 34:11.780
Are molehills which will vanish before the resolutions

34:11.780 --> 34:12.700
Of man.

34:12.700 --> 34:15.100
These feelings are transitory.

34:15.420 --> 34:19.260
Each day of expectation delayed fills them with fear.

34:19.860 --> 34:22.620
And I almost dread a mutiny caused by this despair.

34:25.900 --> 34:27.100
September 5th.

34:27.100 --> 34:29.760
A scene has just passed of such uncommon interest

34:29.760 --> 34:32.860
That although it is highly probable that these papers

34:32.860 --> 34:35.920
May never reach you, yet I cannot forbear recording it.

34:36.780 --> 34:38.860
We are still surrounded by mountains of ice,

34:38.860 --> 34:41.960
Still in imminent danger of being crushed in their conflict.

34:42.620 --> 34:45.960
The cold is excessive, and many of my unfortunate

34:45.960 --> 34:48.560
Comrades have already found a grave amidst this

34:48.560 --> 34:49.940
Scene of desolation.

34:50.960 --> 34:53.140
Frankenstein has daily declined in health.

34:53.540 --> 34:56.160
A feverish fire still glimmers in his eyes.

34:56.340 --> 34:59.640
But he is exhausted, and when suddenly roused to any

34:59.640 --> 35:02.740
Exertion, he speedily sinks again into apparent

35:02.740 --> 35:03.600
Lifelessness.

35:04.600 --> 35:06.980
I mentioned in my last letter the fears

35:06.980 --> 35:08.480
I entertained of a mutiny.

35:09.100 --> 35:12.220
This morning as I sat, watching the wan countenance

35:12.220 --> 35:15.160
Of my friend, his eyes half closed and his limbs

35:15.160 --> 35:18.580
Hanging listlessly, I was roused by half a dozen

35:18.580 --> 35:21.240
Of the sailors who demanded admission into the cabin.

35:22.140 --> 35:24.220
They entered, and their leader addressed me.

35:24.680 --> 35:27.440
He told me that he and his companions had been chosen

35:27.440 --> 35:30.200
By the other sailors to come in deputation to me,

35:30.200 --> 35:33.420
To make a requisition, which injustice I could not

35:33.420 --> 35:34.120
Refuse.

35:35.120 --> 35:38.720
We were immured in ice, and should probably never

35:38.720 --> 35:41.940
Escape, but they feared that if, as was possible,

35:42.000 --> 35:45.020
The ice should dissipate and a free passage be opened,

35:45.260 --> 35:47.640
I should be rash enough to continue my voyage,

35:47.940 --> 35:50.940
And lead them into fresh dangers, after which they

35:50.940 --> 35:52.900
Might happily have surmounted this.

35:54.440 --> 35:57.060
They insisted, therefore, that I should engage with

35:57.060 --> 36:00.060
A solemn promise that if the vessel should be freed,

36:00.540 --> 36:03.080
I would instantly direct my course southward.

36:04.180 --> 36:05.880
Their speech troubled me.

36:06.460 --> 36:09.240
I had not despaired, nor had I yet conceived

36:09.240 --> 36:11.220
The idea of returning if set free.

36:11.740 --> 36:14.840
Yet I could injustice, yet could I injustice,

36:15.080 --> 36:17.540
Or even impossibility, refuse this demand.

36:18.600 --> 36:20.660
I hesitated before I answered,

36:21.360 --> 36:24.200
When Frankenstein, who had at first been silent

36:24.200 --> 36:27.800
And indeed appeared hardly to have force enough to attend,

36:28.220 --> 36:29.480
Now roused himself.

36:30.260 --> 36:33.120
His eyes sparkled, and his cheeks flushed with momentary

36:33.120 --> 36:33.680
Vigor.

36:34.560 --> 36:37.700
Turning towards the men, he said, What do you mean?

36:38.340 --> 36:40.340
What do you demand of your captain?

36:41.100 --> 36:43.620
Are you then so easily turned from your design?

36:44.360 --> 36:46.600
Did you not call this a glorious expedition?

36:47.180 --> 36:48.940
And wherefore was it glorious?

36:48.940 --> 36:53.460
Not because the way was smooth and placid as a southern sea,

36:53.840 --> 36:56.500
But because it was full of dangers and terror,

36:56.940 --> 36:58.440
Because at every new incident,

36:58.960 --> 37:01.980
Your fortitude was to be called forth,

37:02.280 --> 37:04.080
And your courage exhibited,

37:04.640 --> 37:06.840
Because danger and death surrounded it,

37:07.000 --> 37:09.140
And these you were to brave and overcome.

37:10.580 --> 37:13.500
For this it was glorious, and for this it was

37:13.500 --> 37:14.700
An honorable undertaking.

37:14.700 --> 37:17.720
You were hereafter to be hailed

37:17.720 --> 37:19.580
As the benefactors of your species,

37:20.120 --> 37:23.500
Your names adored as belonging to the brave men

37:23.500 --> 37:25.740
Who encountered death for honor,

37:26.080 --> 37:27.500
And the benefit of mankind.

37:28.160 --> 37:31.460
And now, behold, with the first imagination of danger,

37:31.660 --> 37:35.140
Or, if you will, the first mighty and terrific trial

37:35.140 --> 37:37.440
Of your courage, you shrink away,

37:37.580 --> 37:40.080
And are content to be handed down as men

37:40.080 --> 37:43.240
Who had not strength enough to endure cold imperil.

37:44.380 --> 37:46.820
And so poor souls were chilly

37:46.820 --> 37:49.260
And returned to their warm firesides.

37:50.060 --> 37:52.540
Why, that requires not this preparation.

37:53.040 --> 37:54.780
Ye need not have come thus far,

37:54.880 --> 37:57.400
And dragged your captain to the shame of a defeat,

37:57.660 --> 37:59.380
Merely to prove yourself cowards.

38:00.060 --> 38:02.880
Oh, be men, or be more than men.

38:03.180 --> 38:06.020
Be steady to your purposes, and firm as a rock.

38:06.020 --> 38:09.080
This ice is not made of such stuff

38:09.080 --> 38:10.660
As your hearts may be.

38:11.200 --> 38:13.640
It is mutable and cannot withstand you.

38:14.020 --> 38:17.560
If you say that it shall not, do not return to your families

38:17.560 --> 38:20.380
With the stigma of disgrace marked on your brows.

38:20.700 --> 38:23.540
Return as heroes who have fought and conquered,

38:24.260 --> 38:27.500
And who know not what it is to turn back,

38:28.560 --> 38:30.020
Turn their backs on the foe.

38:31.860 --> 38:33.600
He spoke this with a voice

38:33.600 --> 38:36.260
So modulated to the different feelings

38:36.260 --> 38:38.540
Expressed in his speech, with an eye

38:38.540 --> 38:41.380
So full of lofty design and heroism,

38:42.080 --> 38:44.160
That can you wonder that these men were moved?

38:44.680 --> 38:47.780
They looked at one another and were unable to reply.

38:48.560 --> 38:49.280
I spoke.

38:50.320 --> 38:53.260
I told them to retire and consider of what had been said,

38:53.680 --> 38:55.320
That I would not lead them farther north

38:55.320 --> 38:57.480
If they strenuously desired the contrary,

38:57.480 --> 38:59.680
But that I hoped that, with reflection,

38:59.820 --> 39:01.160
Their courage would return.

39:03.000 --> 39:06.080
They retired, and I turned towards my friend,

39:06.200 --> 39:09.280
But he was sunk in languor,

39:10.140 --> 39:11.760
And almost deprived of life.

39:13.260 --> 39:15.560
How all this will terminate, I know not.

39:16.740 --> 39:18.980
But I had rather die than return shamefully,

39:19.320 --> 39:20.720
My purpose unfulfilled.

39:21.700 --> 39:23.420
Yet I fear such will be my fate.

39:23.420 --> 39:26.820
The men, unsupported by ideas of glory and honor,

39:27.060 --> 39:29.400
Can never willingly continue to endure

39:29.400 --> 39:30.520
Their present hardship.

39:33.820 --> 39:36.140
September 7th. The die is cast.

39:36.620 --> 39:39.200
I have consented to return if we are not destroyed.

39:39.840 --> 39:42.720
Thus are my hopes blasted by cowardice and indecision.

39:43.420 --> 39:45.860
I come back ignorant and disappointed.

39:46.880 --> 39:49.720
It requires more philosophy than I possess

39:49.720 --> 39:51.940
To bear this injustice with patience.

39:57.380 --> 39:58.500
September 12th.

39:58.500 --> 39:59.240
It is past.

39:59.360 --> 40:00.600
I am returning to England.

40:00.960 --> 40:03.140
I have lost my hopes of utility and glory.

40:03.580 --> 40:04.720
I have lost my friend.

40:05.500 --> 40:09.240
But I will endeavor to detail these bitter circumstances to you,

40:09.260 --> 40:12.240
My dear sister, and while I am wafted towards England

40:12.240 --> 40:14.600
And towards you, I will not despond.

40:15.860 --> 40:18.300
September 9th. The ice began to move,

40:18.300 --> 40:21.300
And roarings like thunder were heard at a distance,

40:22.240 --> 40:24.340
As the island split and cracked

40:25.380 --> 40:26.760
In every direction.

40:30.000 --> 40:31.780
We were in the most imminent peril,

40:32.100 --> 40:33.660
But as we could only remain passive,

40:33.760 --> 40:36.900
My chief attention was occupied by my unfortunate guest,

40:37.100 --> 40:39.380
Whose illness increased in such a degree

40:39.380 --> 40:42.000
That he was entirely confined to his bed.

40:43.100 --> 40:45.640
The ice cracked behind us and was driven

40:45.640 --> 40:48.000
With force towards the north.

40:48.660 --> 40:50.400
A breeze sprung from the west,

40:51.080 --> 40:54.120
And on the 11th the passage towards the south

40:54.640 --> 40:56.040
Became perfectly free.

40:56.520 --> 40:59.960
When the sailors saw this, and that their return to the native country

40:59.960 --> 41:02.940
Was apparently assured, a shout of tumultuous joy

41:02.940 --> 41:05.460
Broke from them, loud and long continued.

41:06.520 --> 41:09.120
Frankenstein, who was dozing, awoke and asked

41:09.120 --> 41:10.420
The cause of the tumult.

41:10.420 --> 41:13.800
They shout, I said, because they will soon

41:13.800 --> 41:14.760
Return to England.

41:16.560 --> 41:18.140
Do you then really return?

41:19.120 --> 41:21.700
Alas, yes, I cannot withstand their demands.

41:21.900 --> 41:24.300
I cannot lead them unwillingly to danger.

41:24.440 --> 41:25.340
I must return.

41:26.440 --> 41:28.300
Do so, if you will, but I will not.

41:29.080 --> 41:31.920
You may give up your purpose, but mine is assigned to me

41:31.920 --> 41:33.380
By heaven, and I dare not.

41:33.380 --> 41:37.420
I am weak, but surely the spirits who assist my vengeance

41:37.420 --> 41:39.620
Will endow me with sufficient strength.

41:41.020 --> 41:43.340
Saying this, he endeavored to spring from the bed,

41:43.560 --> 41:45.360
But the exertion was too great for him.

41:45.700 --> 41:47.900
He fell back and fainted.

41:49.340 --> 41:51.380
It was not long before he was restored,

41:51.540 --> 41:54.960
And I often thought that life was entirely extinct.

41:57.560 --> 41:59.460
At length he opened his eyes,

41:59.800 --> 42:02.780
He breathed with difficulty, and was unable to speak.

42:02.780 --> 42:05.860
The surgeon gave him a composing draft,

42:06.900 --> 42:09.160
And ordered us to leave him undisturbed.

42:09.500 --> 42:12.380
In the meantime, he told me that my friend

42:12.380 --> 42:14.500
Had certainly not many hours to live.

42:16.240 --> 42:18.080
His sentence was pronounced,

42:18.340 --> 42:21.080
And I could only grieve and be patient.

42:22.140 --> 42:23.900
I sat by his bed, watching him.

42:24.080 --> 42:26.440
His eyes were closed, and I thought he slept.

42:27.520 --> 42:30.060
But presently he called to me in a feeble voice,

42:31.380 --> 42:33.440
And bidding me come near, said,

42:33.900 --> 42:38.240
Alas, the strength I relied on is gone.

42:39.000 --> 42:41.420
I feel that I soon shall die,

42:42.020 --> 42:44.320
And he, my enemy and persecutor,

42:44.520 --> 42:45.820
May still be in being.

42:46.900 --> 42:49.640
Think not, Walton, that in the last moments

42:49.640 --> 42:52.640
Of my existence I feel that burned hatred

42:52.640 --> 42:55.980
And ardent desire of revenge I once expressed,

42:56.320 --> 42:58.960
But I feel myself justified in desiring

42:58.960 --> 43:00.360
The death of my adversary.

43:01.440 --> 43:03.440
During these last days I have been occupied

43:03.440 --> 43:05.360
In examining my past conduct,

43:06.460 --> 43:07.960
Nor do I find it blamable.

43:09.720 --> 43:12.160
In a fit of enthusiastic madness I created

43:12.160 --> 43:15.240
A rational creature and was bound towards him

43:15.240 --> 43:17.340
To assure, as far as was in my power,

43:17.400 --> 43:19.180
His happiness and well-being.

43:19.920 --> 43:22.560
This was my duty, but there was another

43:22.560 --> 43:24.800
Still paramount to that.

43:25.500 --> 43:28.300
My duties towards the beings of my own species

43:28.300 --> 43:30.200
Had greater claims to my attention,

43:30.700 --> 43:32.640
Because they included a greater proportion

43:32.640 --> 43:34.540
Of happiness or misery.

43:36.280 --> 43:38.980
Urged by this view, I refused,

43:39.240 --> 43:42.200
And did right in refusing to create a companion

43:42.200 --> 43:43.400
For the first creature.

43:44.500 --> 43:47.060
He showed unparalleled malignity

43:47.060 --> 43:49.820
And selfishness in evil.

43:52.400 --> 43:53.640
He destroyed my friends.

43:54.680 --> 43:56.060
He devoted to destruction

43:56.060 --> 43:59.280
Beings who possessed exquisite sensations,

43:59.600 --> 44:00.720
Happiness and wisdom.

44:01.360 --> 44:04.380
Nor do I know where this thirst for vengeance may end,

44:04.840 --> 44:08.180
Miserable himself, that he may render no other wretched.

44:08.700 --> 44:09.720
He ought to die.

44:10.440 --> 44:13.600
The task of this destruction was mine, but I have failed.

44:13.600 --> 44:17.740
When actuated by selfish and vicious motives,

44:19.240 --> 44:20.560
I asked you to undertake

44:20.560 --> 44:22.240
My unfinished work,

44:22.600 --> 44:25.060
And I renew this request now,

44:25.340 --> 44:28.460
When I am only induced by reason and virtue.

44:33.800 --> 44:35.880
Yet I cannot ask you to renounce

44:35.880 --> 44:38.920
Your country and friends to fulfill this task.

44:39.740 --> 44:41.680
And now that you are returning to England,

44:43.560 --> 44:46.420
You will have little chance of meeting with him,

44:46.740 --> 44:48.740
But the consideration of these points

44:48.740 --> 44:51.580
And the well-balancing of what you may esteem

44:51.580 --> 44:53.380
Your duties, I leave to you.

44:53.880 --> 44:56.480
My judgment and ideas are already disturbed

44:56.480 --> 44:58.020
By the near approach of death.

44:58.880 --> 45:01.620
I dare not ask you to do what I think right,

45:02.140 --> 45:04.380
For I may still be misled by passion.

45:06.080 --> 45:08.640
That he should live to be an instrument of mischief

45:08.640 --> 45:11.400
Disturbs me in other respects this hour,

45:11.860 --> 45:14.080
When I momentarily expect my release

45:14.080 --> 45:17.280
Is the only happy one which I have enjoyed for several years.

45:18.340 --> 45:20.000
The forms of the beloved dead

45:20.000 --> 45:22.720
Flip before me, and I hasten to their arms.

45:23.340 --> 45:24.620
Farewell, Walton.

45:25.720 --> 45:27.540
Seek happiness in the tranquility,

45:28.300 --> 45:30.780
And avoid ambition, even if it be only

45:30.780 --> 45:33.480
The apparently innocent one of distinguishing yourself

45:33.480 --> 45:34.780
In science and discoveries.

45:35.860 --> 45:37.380
Yet why do I say this?

45:38.040 --> 45:40.460
I have myself been blasted in these hopes.

45:41.480 --> 45:42.780
Yet another may succeed.

45:45.020 --> 45:47.320
His voice became faint as he spoke,

45:47.500 --> 45:49.460
And at length, exhausted by his effort,

45:49.680 --> 45:51.040
He sunk into silence.

45:51.940 --> 45:53.940
About half an hour afterwards,

45:54.080 --> 45:56.180
He attempted again to speak, but was unable.

45:56.180 --> 45:58.540
He pressed my hand feebly,

45:59.220 --> 46:00.820
And his eyes closed forever,

46:01.500 --> 46:03.820
While the irradiation of a gentle smile

46:03.820 --> 46:05.520
Passed away from his lips.

46:07.280 --> 46:09.240
Margaret, what comment can I make

46:09.240 --> 46:11.960
On the untimely extinction of this glorious spirit?

46:12.660 --> 46:14.360
What can I say that will enable you

46:14.360 --> 46:16.200
To understand the depth of my sorrow?

46:17.080 --> 46:18.520
All that I should express

46:18.520 --> 46:20.140
Would be inadequate and feeble.

46:20.780 --> 46:21.760
My tears flow.

46:22.680 --> 46:24.700
My mind is overshadowed by a cold,

46:24.800 --> 46:26.040
A cloud of disappointment.

46:27.220 --> 46:28.900
But I journey towards England,

46:29.700 --> 46:31.780
And I may there find consolation.

46:34.020 --> 46:36.780
I am interrupted. What do these sounds pretend?

46:37.360 --> 46:39.620
It is midnight, the breeze blows fairly,

46:40.160 --> 46:42.440
And the watch on deck scarcely stir.

46:43.660 --> 46:46.040
Again there is a sound as of a human voice,

46:46.160 --> 46:48.600
But horser. It comes from the cabin

46:48.600 --> 46:50.940
Where the remains of Frankenstein still lie.

46:51.580 --> 46:54.300
I must arise and examine. Good night, my sister.

46:56.200 --> 46:58.780
Great God, what a scene has just taken place!

46:59.260 --> 47:01.380
I am yet dizzy with remembrance of it.

47:02.720 --> 47:04.760
I hardly know whether I shall have the power

47:04.760 --> 47:07.680
To detail it, yet the tale which I have recorded

47:07.680 --> 47:09.600
Would be incomplete without this final

47:09.600 --> 47:12.560
And wonderful catastrophe. I enter the cabin

47:12.560 --> 47:16.020
Where lay the remains of my ill-fated and admirable friend.

47:17.960 --> 47:19.740
Over him hung a form

47:19.740 --> 47:21.940
Which I cannot find words to describe,

47:22.380 --> 47:24.740
Gigantic in stature, yet uncouth

47:24.740 --> 47:26.460
And distorted in its proportions.

47:27.260 --> 47:29.960
As he hung over the coffin his face was concealed

47:29.960 --> 47:33.460
By long locks of ragged hair, but one vast hand

47:33.460 --> 47:36.160
Was extended in colour and apparent texture

47:36.160 --> 47:39.080
Like that of a mummy. When he heard the sound

47:39.080 --> 47:41.360
Of my approach he ceased to utter exclamations

47:41.360 --> 47:43.960
Of grief and horror and sprung towards the window.

47:44.740 --> 47:47.620
Never before did I behold a vision

47:47.620 --> 47:51.180
So horrible as his face, of such loathsome

47:51.180 --> 47:53.680
Yet appalling hideousness.

47:54.220 --> 47:57.620
I shut my eyes involuntarily and endeavoured

47:57.620 --> 48:00.380
To recollect what were my duties with regard

48:00.380 --> 48:03.620
To this destroyer. I called on him to stay.

48:03.620 --> 48:06.640
He paused, looking on me with wonder

48:06.640 --> 48:09.120
And again turning towards the lifeless form

48:09.120 --> 48:12.460
Of his creator, he seemed to forget my presence

48:12.460 --> 48:15.820
And every feature and gesture seemed instigated

48:15.820 --> 48:18.620
By the wildest rage of some uncontrollable

48:19.220 --> 48:19.740
Passion.

48:21.740 --> 48:24.620
That is also my victim, he exclaimed.

48:26.560 --> 48:28.260
In his murder my crimes

48:28.260 --> 48:31.200
Are consummated. The miserable series

48:31.200 --> 48:34.420
Of my being is wound to its close.

48:37.440 --> 48:39.000
That is also my victim,

48:39.000 --> 48:41.920
He exclaimed. In his murder

48:41.920 --> 48:44.380
My crimes are consummated.

48:45.320 --> 48:47.720
The miserable series of my being

48:47.720 --> 48:49.460
Is wound to its close.

48:50.780 --> 48:52.380
O Frankenstein,

48:52.980 --> 48:55.380
Generous and self-devoted being,

48:56.620 --> 48:57.840
What does it avail

48:57.840 --> 49:02.000
That I now ask thee to pardon me?

49:02.500 --> 49:04.880
I, who irretrievably

49:04.880 --> 49:07.880
Destroyed thee by destroying all thou lovest,

49:09.020 --> 49:11.260
Alas, he is cold.

49:12.300 --> 49:14.120
He cannot answer me.

49:15.860 --> 49:17.700
His voice seemed suffocated

49:17.700 --> 49:20.500
And my first impulses, which had suggested

49:20.500 --> 49:23.300
To me the duty of obeying the dying request

49:23.300 --> 49:25.780
Of my friend in destroying his enemy

49:25.780 --> 49:27.880
Were now suspended by a mixture

49:27.880 --> 49:29.600
Of curiosity and compassion.

49:30.840 --> 49:32.420
I approached this tremendous being.

49:32.660 --> 49:35.220
I dared not again raise my eyes to his face.

49:35.440 --> 49:37.600
There was something so scarring and unearthly

49:37.600 --> 49:38.760
In its ugliness.

49:41.340 --> 49:44.300
I attempted to speak, but the words

49:44.300 --> 49:46.800
Died away on my lips. The monster continued

49:46.800 --> 49:49.780
To utter wild and incoherent self-reproaches.

49:49.780 --> 49:53.160
At length I gathered resolution

49:53.160 --> 49:56.160
To address him in a pause of the tempest

49:56.160 --> 49:57.000
Of his passion.

49:59.100 --> 50:02.080
Your repentance, I said, is now superfluous.

50:02.380 --> 50:04.440
If you had listened to the voice of conscience

50:04.440 --> 50:06.500
And heeded the strings of remorse

50:06.500 --> 50:09.440
Before you had urged your diabolical vengeance

50:09.440 --> 50:12.360
To this extremity, Frankenstein would yet have lived.

50:14.640 --> 50:16.140
And do you dream?

50:16.140 --> 50:17.120
Said the demon.

50:18.460 --> 50:21.300
Do you think that I was then dead to agony and remorse?

50:22.040 --> 50:24.500
He, he continued pointing to the corpse,

50:25.200 --> 50:28.000
He suffered not in the consummation of the deed.

50:28.500 --> 50:31.860
Oh, not the ten thousandth portion

50:31.860 --> 50:34.160
Of the anguish that was mine during the lingering

50:34.160 --> 50:35.780
Detail of its execution.

50:37.460 --> 50:39.780
A frightful selfishness hurried me on

50:39.780 --> 50:43.620
While my heart was poisoned with remorse.

50:45.420 --> 50:47.500
Think you that the groans

50:47.500 --> 50:50.460
Of Clairvaux were music to my ears?

50:52.280 --> 50:53.920
My heart was fashioned

50:53.920 --> 50:56.960
To be susceptible of love

50:56.960 --> 51:00.100
And sympathy, and when wretched

51:00.100 --> 51:02.320
By the misery of vice and hatred

51:02.320 --> 51:05.780
It did not endure the violence of the charred change

51:05.780 --> 51:09.100
Without torture such as you cannot even imagine.

51:10.720 --> 51:12.380
After the murder of Clairvaux

51:12.380 --> 51:15.160
While I returned to Switzerland heartbroken and overcome,

51:15.420 --> 51:18.760
I pitied Frankenstein, my pity amounted to horror.

51:19.380 --> 51:20.720
I abhorred myself.

51:21.560 --> 51:24.540
But when I discovered that he, the author at once

51:24.540 --> 51:27.840
Of my existence and of its unspeakable torments

51:27.840 --> 51:29.500
Dared to hope for happiness,

51:30.060 --> 51:33.620
That while he accumulated wretchedness and despair upon me

51:33.620 --> 51:36.780
He sought his own enjoyment in feelings and passions

51:36.780 --> 51:40.560
From the indulgence of which I was forever barred,

51:40.560 --> 51:43.640
Then impotent envy and bitter indignation

51:43.640 --> 51:47.520
Filled me with an insatiable thirst for vengeance.

51:48.900 --> 51:50.380
I recollected my threat

51:51.300 --> 51:53.840
And resolved that it should be accomplished.

51:54.620 --> 51:56.520
I knew that I was preparing myself

51:56.520 --> 51:59.380
For a deadly torture, but I was the slave

51:59.380 --> 52:02.860
Not the master of an impulse

52:02.860 --> 52:05.840
Which I detested, yet I could not disobey.

52:07.400 --> 52:10.060
Yes, when she died,

52:10.460 --> 52:11.980
Nay, then I was not miserable.

52:13.140 --> 52:16.260
I had cast off all feelings, subdued all anguish

52:16.260 --> 52:18.680
To riot in the excess of my despair.

52:20.040 --> 52:22.260
Evil, thencefore, became my good.

52:24.200 --> 52:27.200
Urged thus far, I had no choice

52:27.200 --> 52:29.620
But to adapt my nature to an element

52:29.620 --> 52:31.400
Which I had willingly chosen.

52:32.220 --> 52:34.860
The completion of my demonical design

52:34.860 --> 52:38.540
Became an insatiable passion, and now it has ended.

52:39.160 --> 52:41.220
There is my last victim.

52:44.380 --> 52:47.620
I was at first touched by the expression of his misery,

52:48.460 --> 52:50.600
Yet when I called to mind what Frankenstein

52:50.600 --> 52:53.560
Had said of his powers of eloquence and persuasion,

52:54.340 --> 52:56.580
And when I again cast my eyes

52:56.580 --> 52:58.820
On the lifeless form of my friend,

52:59.620 --> 53:01.860
Indignation was rekindled within me.

53:02.760 --> 53:05.100
Wretch, I said, it is well that you come here

53:05.100 --> 53:07.480
To whine over the desolation that you have made.

53:07.940 --> 53:10.240
You throw a torch into a pile of buildings,

53:10.780 --> 53:13.040
And when they are consumed you sit among the ruins

53:13.040 --> 53:15.920
And lament the fall, hypocritical fiend.

53:16.300 --> 53:20.300
If he whom you mourn still lived, still would he be the object.

53:20.500 --> 53:22.500
Again would he become the prey

53:22.500 --> 53:24.480
Of your accursed vengeance.

53:25.160 --> 53:27.280
It is not pity that you feel.

53:27.760 --> 53:31.420
You lament only because the victim of your malignity

53:31.420 --> 53:33.580
Is withdrawn from your power.

53:36.440 --> 53:38.280
Oh, it is not thus,

53:38.540 --> 53:40.600
Not thus interrupted the being.

53:41.620 --> 53:44.260
Yet such must be the impression conveyed to you

53:44.260 --> 53:47.400
By what appears to be the purport of my actions.

53:48.220 --> 53:50.840
Yet I seek not a fellow feeling in my misery.

53:51.660 --> 53:53.640
No sympathy may I ever find.

53:55.780 --> 53:59.160
When I first sought it, it was the love of virtue,

53:59.960 --> 54:01.980
The feelings of happiness and affection,

54:02.920 --> 54:04.560
With which my whole being overflowed

54:05.080 --> 54:06.820
That I wished to be participated.

54:08.140 --> 54:10.980
But now that virtue has become to me a shadow,

54:11.500 --> 54:13.520
And that happiness and affection are turned

54:13.520 --> 54:15.280
Into bitter and loathing despair,

54:15.880 --> 54:17.660
In what should I seek for sympathy?

54:18.620 --> 54:20.560
I am content to suffer alone,

54:20.560 --> 54:23.300
While my suffering shall endure.

54:24.000 --> 54:26.500
When I die, I am well satisfied

54:26.500 --> 54:28.840
That abhorrence and opprobrium

54:29.340 --> 54:30.640
Should load my memory.

54:32.980 --> 54:35.380
Once my fancy was soothed

54:35.380 --> 54:38.620
With dreams of virtue, of fame, and of enjoyment.

54:39.360 --> 54:42.120
Once I falsely hoped to meet with beings who,

54:42.320 --> 54:44.880
Pardoning my outward form, would love me

54:44.880 --> 54:46.280
For the excellent qualities

54:46.280 --> 54:48.260
Which I was capable of unfolding.

54:49.220 --> 54:52.420
I was nourished with high thoughts of honor and devotion.

54:53.380 --> 54:55.220
But now crime has degraded me

54:55.220 --> 54:56.800
Beneath the meanest animal.

54:57.320 --> 54:59.700
No guilt, no mischief,

55:00.160 --> 55:02.020
No malignity, no misery

55:02.020 --> 55:04.880
Can be found comparable to mine.

55:06.060 --> 55:08.820
When I run over the frightful catalogue of my sins,

55:08.880 --> 55:11.140
I cannot believe that I am the same creature

55:11.140 --> 55:13.740
Whose thoughts were once filled with sublime

55:13.740 --> 55:16.640
And transcendent visions of the beauty

55:16.640 --> 55:18.080
And the majesty of goodness.

55:19.120 --> 55:21.280
But it is even so.

55:22.180 --> 55:24.660
The fallen angel becomes a malignant devil.

55:25.780 --> 55:28.480
Yet even that enemy of God and man

55:28.480 --> 55:31.940
Had friends and associates in his desolation.

55:33.060 --> 55:34.580
I am alone.

55:36.500 --> 55:39.060
You who call Frankenstein your friend

55:39.060 --> 55:42.160
Seem to have a knowledge of my crimes and his misfortunes.

55:43.020 --> 55:45.520
But in the detail which he gave you

55:45.520 --> 55:48.600
Of them he could not sum up the hours

55:48.600 --> 55:51.280
And months of misery which I endured

55:51.280 --> 55:53.520
Wasting in impotent passions.

55:54.360 --> 55:56.260
For while I destroyed his hopes

55:56.260 --> 55:58.580
I did not satisfy my own desires.

55:59.540 --> 56:02.180
They were forever ardent and craving.

56:03.960 --> 56:06.360
Still I desired love

56:06.360 --> 56:07.920
And fellowship.

56:09.320 --> 56:12.080
And I was still spurned.

56:13.040 --> 56:14.840
Was there no injustice in this?

56:15.860 --> 56:17.780
Am I to be thought the only criminal

56:18.310 --> 56:21.540
When all humankind simmed against me?

56:22.940 --> 56:24.460
Why do you not hate Felix

56:24.460 --> 56:28.360
Who drove his friend from the door with contumely?

56:29.460 --> 56:30.740
Why do you not execrate

56:30.740 --> 56:32.580
The rustic who sought to destroy

56:32.580 --> 56:34.440
The savior of his child?

56:34.940 --> 56:38.440
Nay, these are virtuous and immaculate beings.

56:38.620 --> 56:40.900
I, the miserable and the abandoned

56:40.900 --> 56:43.860
Am an abortion to be spurned at,

56:44.200 --> 56:47.080
Kicked and trampled on.

56:49.460 --> 56:51.160
Even now my blood boils

56:51.160 --> 56:52.980
At the recollection of this injustice.

56:53.940 --> 56:55.800
But it is true that I am a wretch.

56:56.020 --> 56:58.180
I have murdered the lovely and the helpless.

56:58.180 --> 57:00.760
I have strangled the innocent as they slept

57:00.760 --> 57:02.980
And grasped to death his throat

57:02.980 --> 57:06.960
Who never injured me or any other living thing.

57:08.980 --> 57:10.300
I have devoted my creator

57:10.300 --> 57:13.360
The select specimen of all that is worthy of love

57:13.360 --> 57:15.480
And admiration among men to misery.

57:16.220 --> 57:17.800
I have pursued him

57:17.800 --> 57:21.720
Even to that irredeemable ruin.

57:22.580 --> 57:25.580
There he lies, white and cold in death.

57:25.580 --> 57:29.360
You hate me, but your abhorrence cannot equal

57:29.360 --> 57:31.380
That with which I regard myself.

57:32.100 --> 57:34.880
I look on the hands which executed the deed

57:34.880 --> 57:36.180
I think of the heart

57:36.920 --> 57:40.060
In which the imagination of it was conceived

57:40.580 --> 57:43.920
And long for the moment when these hands will meet my eyes

57:43.920 --> 57:47.960
When that imagination will haunt my thoughts no more.

57:48.600 --> 57:50.360
Fear not that I shall be instrument

57:50.360 --> 57:51.720
Of future mischief.

57:51.720 --> 57:54.000
My work is nearly complete.

57:54.560 --> 57:57.660
Neither yours nor any man's death

57:57.660 --> 58:00.720
Is needed to consummate the series of my being

58:00.720 --> 58:03.740
And accomplish that which must be done.

58:04.020 --> 58:05.520
But it requires my own.

58:07.800 --> 58:10.320
Do not think that I shall be slow

58:10.320 --> 58:12.100
To perform this sacrifice.

58:12.940 --> 58:15.620
I shall quit your vessel on the ice raft

58:15.620 --> 58:17.100
Which brought me thither

58:17.100 --> 58:20.480
And shall seek the most northern extremity of the globe.

58:20.820 --> 58:22.520
I shall collect my funeral pile

58:22.920 --> 58:26.280
And consume to ashes this miserable frame

58:26.640 --> 58:28.160
That it remains.

58:29.000 --> 58:32.180
Its remains may afford no light to any curious

58:32.180 --> 58:35.080
And unhallowed wretch who would create

58:35.080 --> 58:36.600
Such another as I have been.

58:37.420 --> 58:40.960
I shall die. I shall no longer feel the agonies

58:40.960 --> 58:42.500
Which now consume me

58:42.500 --> 58:46.780
Or be the prey of feelings unsatisfied yet unquenched.

58:47.820 --> 58:48.680
He is dead

58:48.680 --> 58:50.720
Who called me into being

58:51.400 --> 58:53.140
And when I shall be no more

58:53.140 --> 58:57.060
The very remembrance of us both will speedily vanish.

58:58.180 --> 59:00.360
I shall no longer see the sun or stars

59:00.360 --> 59:03.300
Or feel the winds play on my cheeks.

59:04.000 --> 59:07.440
Light, feeling and sense will pass away

59:08.180 --> 59:09.900
And in this condition

59:10.680 --> 59:12.780
Must I find my happiness.

59:16.120 --> 59:17.200
Some years ago

59:17.200 --> 59:18.360
When the images

59:18.900 --> 59:22.180
Which this world affords first opened upon me

59:22.180 --> 59:24.680
When I felt the cheering warmth of summer

59:24.680 --> 59:28.460
And heard the rustling of the leaves and the warbling of the birds

59:28.460 --> 59:30.840
And these were all to me

59:30.840 --> 59:32.960
I should have wept to die.

59:33.740 --> 59:36.220
Now it is my only consolation

59:36.220 --> 59:40.080
Polluted by crimes and torn by the bitterest remorse

59:40.080 --> 59:43.500
Where can I find rest but in death?

59:45.800 --> 59:46.400
Farewell

59:47.040 --> 59:50.680
I leave you and in the last of the humankind

59:51.400 --> 59:53.100
Whom these eyes

59:53.100 --> 59:54.940
Will ever behold.

59:55.720 --> 59:57.240
Farewell, Frankenstein

59:57.240 --> 01:00:01.540
If thou were yet alive and yet cherished a desire of revenge against me

01:00:01.540 --> 01:00:05.520
It would be better satiated in my life than in my destruction

01:00:05.520 --> 01:00:07.840
But it was not so

01:00:07.840 --> 01:00:10.000
Thou didst not seek my extinction

01:00:10.400 --> 01:00:13.040
That I might not cause greater wretchedness

01:00:13.040 --> 01:00:16.840
And if yet in some mode unknown to me thou hadst not ceased

01:00:16.840 --> 01:00:20.420
To think and feel thou wouldst not desire against me

01:00:20.420 --> 01:00:22.680
A vengeance greater than that which I feel

01:00:23.520 --> 01:00:25.080
Blasted as thou wert

01:00:25.080 --> 01:00:28.700
My agony was still superior to thine

01:00:28.700 --> 01:00:30.860
For the bitter sting of remorse

01:00:30.860 --> 01:00:33.660
Will not cease to rankle in my wounds until death

01:00:33.660 --> 01:00:35.180
Shall I close them forever

01:00:37.460 --> 01:00:40.680
But soon, he cried with sad and solemn enthusiasm

01:00:40.680 --> 01:00:42.680
I shall die

01:00:42.680 --> 01:00:44.980
And what I now feel

01:00:45.960 --> 01:00:47.900
Be no longer felt

01:00:48.840 --> 01:00:52.340
Soon these burning miseries will be extinct

01:00:53.100 --> 01:00:56.100
I shall ascend my funeral pile

01:00:56.940 --> 01:00:57.580
Triumphantly

01:00:58.720 --> 01:01:02.480
And exult in the agony of the torturing flames

01:01:04.880 --> 01:01:07.280
The light of that conflagration

01:01:08.500 --> 01:01:10.300
Will fade away

01:01:11.020 --> 01:01:13.960
My ashes will be swept into the sea by the winds

01:01:13.960 --> 01:01:17.120
My spirit will sleep in peace

01:01:17.120 --> 01:01:19.200
Or if it thinks

01:01:20.100 --> 01:01:22.380
It will not surely think thus

01:01:23.840 --> 01:01:24.400
Farewell

01:01:27.140 --> 01:01:29.460
He sprung from the cabin window

01:01:29.460 --> 01:01:32.380
As he said this, upon the ice raft

01:01:32.380 --> 01:01:33.980
Which lay close to the vessel

01:01:35.080 --> 01:01:37.480
He was soon borne away by the waves

01:01:37.480 --> 01:01:40.140
And lost in darkness and distance

01:01:43.040 --> 01:01:44.160
The end

01:01:53.900 --> 01:01:53.980
Thanks for watching

